summary:
The oral mucosa is consistently composed of **stratified squamous epithelium**, regardless of regional variation in keratinization (e.g., keratinized in hard palate versus non-keratinized in lips). This structural feature distinguishes it from other types such as simple squamous or columnar epithelium found elsewhere in the body.  

Final Answer: \boxed{\text{B}}  

Note: Despite differences between sites within the mouth, the overarching histologic identity of the oral mucosa is always stratified squamous due to its multilayered protective design.

